s://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60027950"/></author></dc:creator><dc:description><abstract xmlns="" original="n" perspective="ABSCREATE" xml:lang="eng"> <ce:para>Lyd√©ric Bocquet and colleagues have demonstrated that it is possible to greatly increase the migration speed of colloidal particles by linking the particles transport to a fast carrier species. The carriers of choice are simple salts, KCl, NaCl and LiCl, and the phenomenon is demonstrated using a microfluidic device with three inlets. The salt is added into the central inlet, or it is added to a particle-free buffer solution that is injected into the two side inlets. The dominant contribution to diffusiophoresis is electrophoresis of the particles in a macroscopic electric field induced by diffusion of the electrolyte for charged colloidal particles immersed in a gradient of electrolyte concentration. Electrical stresses that are generated along the surface of the particle propel it towards higher concentrations of KCI, regardless of the sign of charge on the particle.</ce:para> </abstract></dc:description><link href="https://api.elsevier.com/content/abstract/scopus_id/52649105320" rel="self"/><link href="https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&amp;scp=52649105320&amp;origin=inward" rel="scopus"/><link href="https://www.scopus.com/inward/citedby.uri?partnerID=HzOxMe3b&amp;scp=52649105320&amp;origin=inward" rel="scopus-citedby"/></coredata><affiliation id="60027950" href="https://api.elsevier.com/content/affiliation/affiliation_id/60027950"><affilname>Carnegie Mellon University</affilname><affiliation-city>Pittsburgh</affiliation-city><affiliation-country>United States</affiliation-country></affiliation><authors><author seq="1" auid="7004536495"><ce:initials>D.C.</ce:initials><ce:indexed-name>Prieve D.C.</ce:indexed-name><ce:surname>Prieve</ce:surname><ce:given-name>Dennis C.</ce:given-name><preferred-name><ce:initials>D.C.</ce:initials><ce:indexed-name>Prieve D.<